title: Add sinon-chrome type definitions
body:
Last one! This adds type definitions for [Sinon-Chrome](https://github.com/vitalets/sinon-chrome): the Chrome.\* API stubbing library.

This one might be a bit contentious: to use it, you have to cast window.chrome (as exposed by chrome itself) to `typeof SinonChrome`, and then you're allowed to use the stubbing API. In addition, because normally the stubbing API methods don't exist on window.chrome, it's not a valid cast, so you have to cast to `any` first. There's a little bit of docs explaining that at the top of the definition. 

This sounds a bit mad, but I think it's the only way.

This is necessary because when you want to compile your test code with your production code (to ensure the tests correctly use the production code), and your production code has to depend on window.chrome being the real Chrome API, not the test library (you don't want stubbing calls in your real code!). Thus, `window.chrome` normally needs to appear to be the real Chrome API everywhere, including the tests. The only practical workarounds I found to make that work are this, and I can't seem to get rid of the `any` sadly, as TypeScript doesn't really believe the cast is a good idea.

Another issue with this is that all the types are a bit general: everything is sinon stubs because Sinon's type definitions don't seem to support any sort of generics to make them more specific. Some of this is potentially avoidable in future, and I'm going look at locking those down a bit eventually (particularly the event callbacks, since that might actually come up in tests quite a bit), but I think it's better to get this in as-is first, and go from there.

This does work though: I'm using this in quite a large Chrome extension codebase and it happily handles all the API I'm stubbing in places, with just this one single messy line at the top of the tests.

title: React: Include required render() function in base React.Component class.
body:
The new TSX mode in the TypeScript compiler has the requirements that
the element class constructor produces an element instance type that is
assignable to the type `JSX.ElementClass`.  To meet this `React.Component<P, S>`
must declare `render(): JSX.Element`.  Derived classes can be more
specific.

This should resolve my issues with running React-Router with the TSX mode, which caused Microsoft/TypeScript#3928 to be reopened.

@RyanCavanaugh @vvakame @vsiao

title: httpBackend updated to match Angular documentation
body:
Changes to httpBackend to conform to angular documentation here: https://code.angularjs.org/1.3.16/docs/api/ngMock/service/$httpBackend
Mainly add the option to pass a function in the url parameter for expect and when function flavors. Updated IRequestHandler respond function to return an IRequestHandler, updated overloads.
Used union types to reduce over 100 overloads to 19 signatures.
Added documentation and tests.
